<HEADLINE>
<P>
GOLF ROUNDUP; 
</P>
<P>
B.C. OPEN IS INITIAL WIN FOR HENKE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Tour sophomore Nolan Henke shot a three-under-par 68 Sunday to outlast Barry 
Jaeckel and hold off Mark Wiebe and earn his first PGA victory in the $700,000 
B.C. Open at Endicott, N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
Henke, who never trailed in the tournament after sharing the first-round lead 
with Jim Hallet, finished 72 holes at En-Joie Golf Course in 268, 16 under par, 
and three strokes better than Wiebe, who overtook Jaeckel for second when he 
birdied No. 18 for a final-round 64. 
</P>
<P>
"I just tried to stay calm," said Henke. "I knew I could screw up. I just 
didn't want to screw up too bad." 
</P>
<P>
Jaeckel, who started the day three strokes behind Henke, pulled within a stroke 
of the lead on the 10th hole, but lost any chance of overtaking Henke when he 
suffered bogeys on 14 and 15. 
</P>
<P>
Tied with Jaeckel at 272 were Doug Tewell with a 67, Brian Tennyson, 66, and 
Jim Benepe, 68. 
</P>
<P>
Jim Dent, six shots off the lead when the final round began, shot a 
seven-under-par 65 and won the Senior Tour event at Richmond, Va., by a stroke 
over Lee Trevino. 
</P>
<P>
Dent's 14-under-par 202 total tied the 54-hole tournament record set two years 
ago by Arnold Palmer. 
</P>
<P>
Dent's fourth victory of the year earned him $52,000 and pushed him into second 
place on the earnings list with $583,377. 
</P>
<P>
Trevino set a single-season money record with the $28,000 he earned for second 
place after a final-round 67 over the 6,444-yard Hermitage Country Club course. 
</P>
<P>
He now has won $740,212, eclipsing Bob Charles' mark of $725,157 set last year. 
</P>
<P>
Second-round leader Gary Player was still in front at 15 under until he bogeyed 
three of the last six holes for a 73 that left him in third place at 204. 
</P>
<P>
Ian Woosnam of Wales beat Mark McNulty of Zimbabwe, 4 and 2, at Virginia Water, 
England, to win his second World Match Play title in four years. 
</P>
<P>
The runner-up to England's Nick Faldo last year and a winner in 1987, Woosnam 
had McNulty chasing him all day. 
</P>
<P>
Woosnam missed a short putt on the 29th hole that would have given him a 
two-hole lead. At the 30th, McNulty had to concede a Woosnam birdie and the 
Welshman stood two up with six to play. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Game Story; Wire 
</P>
