<HEADLINE>
<P>
THOMAS MCGRATH; POET WAS BLACKLISTED IN '50S 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
MINNEAPOLIS 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Thomas McGrath, 73, poet and professor blacklisted during the 1950s McCarthy 
era, died on Thursday after a long illness. 
</P>
<P>
McGrath, who was fired by Cal State Los Angeles for his refusal to testify 
before a government committee investigating communism, worked as a film writer 
and factory and farm worker until the 1960s, when he was hired to teach at 
North Dakota State University. He retired in 1981 from Moorhead State 
University in Minnesota. 
</P>
<P>
McGrath wrote 20 books of poetry and fiction. He achieved his greatest fame 
with "Selected Poems, 1938-88," which won the 1989 Lenore Marshall-Nation Prize 
and the first Minnesota Book Award for poetry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Obituary; Wire 
</P>
